##Six orderlies finally found a place

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

Jin Caiyu (middle) and other nurses went to the street for help, hoping to arrange admission.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
This article is about 3393 words

Estimated reading time 9 minutes

###By Wang Lin, China Youth Daily

Editor | Zhang Guo

After the city's closure was announced on January 23, nine million people stayed behind, while six nurses and aunts who were caring for patients at Wuhan's Central Hospital soon found themselves with nowhere to go.

When the epidemic spread, the nurses took care of retired cadres in the cadres'wards. Their home are in the countryside, to Wuhan is round-the-clock care of patients living, eating and living in the hospital, no fixed residence. After the outbreak intensified, to avoid cross-infection, the hospital asked all nurses to leave, their care of patients to nurses.

The most difficult time, these aunties can only hide in the hospital to hit the floor. Some people have pneumonia symptoms, it is difficult to get timely resettlement.

Jin Caiyu, 61, is one of them. On January 27, Jin and her patients were transferred from the back Lake Hospital area of Wuhan Central Hospital to the Nanjing Road Hospital area. The HOUHU hospital area has been designated as a new crown pneumonia designated hospital, other patients have been transferred out.

After the Lake Hospital District Nurses Remind Jin Caiyu, the hospital has been infected with new crown pneumonia, including many doctors and nurses, told her must wash hands frequently, wear a mask. Wuhan General Hospital is one of the hospitals with the highest number of infections among medical staff.

By early February, new cases and suspected cases of pneumonia had also been confirmed in the hospital district of Nanjing Road, Wuhan's Central Hospital. Another nurse, Tao Mingjuan, remembers coughing in the corridor of the hospital those days. She was afraid. In recent years, Tao Mingjuan has spent most of her time as a nurse. Before the Spring Festival, heard that Wuhan appeared can "person-to-person" disease, she and several fellow villagers originally intended to return home together. But on January 23rd the city was suddenly closed and the road home was cut off.

On the night of February 10, the patient in Kim's care developed fever, and a subsequent CT scan revealed viral infection in the lungs. The hospital quickly quarantined the patient and then transferred him to a designated hospital. Jin caiyu became a "close contact" who needed isolation.

The children of the elderly in the field, the last year are in the care of Jin caiyu. Hearing of his father's illness, the old man's son transferred 500 yuan to Jin Caiyu as a thank you.

On Feb. 11, Kim used the money to go to the hospital for a CT scan. "I had a little cough, too, and I was scared because I was taking care of my dad, " she said. Luckily, she had bronchitis, not new pneumonia.

But other staff stranded at the hospital were not so lucky. From February 11 to 13, another five nurses, Tao Mingjuan, Wang Zhenxian, Liu Guiming, Yin Zhifen and Chen Huanzi, were diagnosed as pulmonary viral infection by CT.. There was a shortage of kits, they couldn't do a nucleic acid test, they couldn't get a diagnosis. There are more confirmed and suspected cases in hospitals, nurses work around the clock to care for patients, and doctors have difficulty determining the source of their infections.

On February 12, the hospital asked the nurses to leave the hospital. A nurse reminds them that they can seek help from nearby streets and communities, report their illness, and arrange for isolation and treatment. According to the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Command at that time, the hospital admitted new pneumonia patients, only through community liaison to arrange beds.

From that day on, the six nurses went to the nearby street offices to report the situation, but all failed. Street offices and neighborhood committee workers said they could not arrange isolation and treatment because they did not have a residence or household registration in Wuhan, and could only register their names, phone numbers, symptoms and other basic information and wait for arrangements.

After hospitals and streets said they could not arrange isolation and treatment, they panicked. "I never thought it would happen like this, " Tao said.

Tao Mingjuan has worked as a nurse in Wuhan for nearly 10 years. Because of her age, her husband's health is not good, last Spring Festival family advised her not to go out to work, but she still want to take advantage of the convenience of the legs, to the Big Hospital in Wuhan to find work. When her son graduated from graduate school two years ago, she worried about finding him a partner, trying to save up more money. As a nurse in Wuhan, you can earn at least 130 yuan a day, which is much higher than the income from farming in your hometown. The outbreak threw her off course.

In desperation, Jin Caiyu and others to give them the introduction of the work of the Domestic Service Agency for help. The head of the company Nie Laxian was Home Quarantine in Wuhan, but also very worried about them. "They are all over 55, they don't have the education, they don't know how to use their smartphones, they don't even know how to save their phone and send text messages. What can they do? "

Nie Laxian turned to 110,120, the mayor's hotline, the streets and the community for help, but could not find a place to take the six nurses.

The nurses are migrant workers who care for retired cadres in the cadre wards of the Central Hospital, but have no fixed residence in Wuhan, are older and do not know how to seek help from other sources, he said in an online appeal. In this case, the infection may be aggravated at any time life-threatening, living on the street will also be infected with the possibility of others.

A volunteer noticed the request and tried to contact and ask for help.

On the night of February 12, several nurses with nowhere to go had to find their own way. Jin caiyu found a fellow countryman and hid in a hospital room overnight. Wang Zhenxian, Chen Huanzi in the hospital clinic building to find a corner, crowded overnight. Yin Zhifen, Tao Mingjuan, Liu Guiming 3 people found a few pieces of paper Shell, pad in the cold corridor, holding the quilt Nestle together.

Over the past few days, several meetings were held in Hubei Province and Wuhan, and the principle of "all revenues should be collected and all governance should be carried out" was put forward, to promote new pneumonia confirmed patients, suspected patients, can not rule out the possibility of infection in patients with fever, confirmed patients close contacts of the "four categories of people" classified centralized treatment.

Jin Caiyu and Wang Zhenxian, who are among the six people who use smartphones, also saw the same thing. For several days, they repeatedly reported their difficulties to nearby streets, police stations and communities.

"We told the street that no matter what, there had to be a place to shelter from the wind and rain, and we begged them to make arrangements. We went there every day from the 11th to the 13th, three or four times a day, but it was always the same, " Jin recalled.

Of the six, only Jin caiyu's CT results were normal. She knew that the longer she spent with the other five people who were already showing signs of infection, the more likely she was to get it. But the hospital wouldn't let her stay, the community couldn't arrange it, and she had nowhere else to go, so she had to wear a double mask and stay with everyone.

The mask was given to her by a nurse. She had helped vacate the ward and carry supplies, and the nurse had stuffed a box of masks into her mouth. These masks are not disposable surgical masks, and they have a strange smell. But the mask was in short supply, and Jin Caiyu insisted on wearing it. In hindsight, it was probably the most direct help she received.

On the night of February 13, six people spent another night in the hospital corridor. The hospital did not allow them to remain in the hospital, but because they had nowhere else to go, the security guards did not take enforcement measures.

They go to the street during the day to continue to ask for help, or at the hospital flower bed side to look for news, at night, "take the opportunity to get into the hospital aisle, crowded together for warmth. ". The iron chairs and floors in the hallway are equally cold, Ms. Yin said.

More impressive than that is the lies they tell their families. Kim used to video-chat with her family almost every night, but on the night of Feb. 13, she lied to them about staying at a small hostel near the hospital, "living with some old sisters. It's good. ".

The son does not rest assured, sent several video invitations, have been refused by Jin caiyu. She made excuses, said the lack of traffic, not enough phone bills. After a while, her son to charge her phone, she said the signal is not good. "after so many years outside, I don't want to worry about my family. "

Yin zhifen considers himself a very strong man. Since the city was shut down, she has spoken to her family much less often than before. When the family asked, she said she was fine at the hospital. But deep down, she didn't want to hang up. Her daughter in law had a baby last year, and her grandson was babbling, so she wanted to hear more.

The hardest day was February 14th. This Day, Wuhan begins to drop temperature considerably, the evening is more wind and rain mix, some places still fluttered snow. Six people haven't had a hot meal in two days. They can only eat the cookies they bought before. They also bought instant noodles, but there was no hot water.

And that was the day of the change. Volunteers and journalists verified the information and reported it to the epidemic prevention and Control Headquarters in Wuhan and Jiang'an District. That night, China Youth Daily reached a quarantine point in Jiang'an District through Jiang'an District's civil affairs bureau.

It was not until midnight that the wind and rain eased off a little. Around the early morning of February 15, with everyone's help, six nurses moved into the isolation point.

Meals for six orderlies at the isolation point.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Depending on their condition, they were transferred to different hospitals. On February 17, Liu was transferred to China Resources Wugang Hospital for treatment. On February 18, Wang Zhenxian and Yin Zhifen were transferred to Zhongnan Hospital, while Jin Caiyu and Chen Huanzi, both of whom had mild symptoms, were sent to the two bokeh hospitals. On February 22, Tao Mingjuan was transferred from the isolation point to Xinhua Hospital for treatment.

At the quarantine site and at the hospital, they underwent CT scans and nucleic acid tests, with varying results. Chen Huanzi and Tao Mingjuan both tested negative for nucleic acid, and the CT was negative for viral pneumonia. Yin Zhifen is waiting for her results. Liu guiming has done 4 times nucleic acid examination before and after, the result of first two times is unknown, the result of last two times is negative. Wang Zhenxian has been tested for nucleic acid 4 times so far, the first test result is negative, the second test result is positive, the latter two results have not been obtained. "The nurse said the nucleic acid test wasn't accurate and asked us to do it more often. "

Only Jin Caiyu, did 2 nucleic acid and 3 CT tests, the results were normal. "We're old sisters in the same boat, " she reassured the others. "We'll be fine. "

Jin caiyu's hometown is Zhijiang, Hubei Province. She's never been out of town before. But by the Spring Festival in 2020, the family of eight was spread out in several places. Because of the epidemic, the eldest son's family stayed in Guangzhou, the younger son's family stayed in Yichang, while the 64-year-old husband stayed in his hometown. She hoped that the epidemic would soon end, and she would return to her hometown and, if possible, send the children home to "make up for a new year. ".

After being hospitalized, Liu guiming feels that his body recovers quite well, listens to the nurse to say that again has a period of time oneself to be able to leave the hospital. But here's what she's worried about: Since she doesn't have a home in Wuhan, she'll need to be kept under observation after she leaves the hospital, and this time, she hopes the authorities will find her a suitable place to live.

(Wang Jiaxing contributed research)
